unclear: Nothing was unclear. Everything went excellent technically and comprehensively. The stories, questions, answers, and instructions were all easy to understand and navigating through the survey was simple.
comments: Thank you so much for choosing me to participate in this study! I was able to grab the last spot available and I enjoyed reading all of the stories, whether they were good or bad. I feel like I answered neutral quite a bit but I do believe a bulk of the people out of12 are not bad people (but I don't know them enough to say they are good people). A lot of these stories require outside information, a better look into their lives, and are situational. A certain story in there had a situation that was tough for everyone and seemed very hard for someone so young to navigate. I hope these people are able to rest at night knowing that they did the best they could and that things will be better in the future. Please thank these people (on my behalf and because they deserve it) for sharing their stories. Good luck with the data you guys collect!

Because as much as a single episode or event in a persons life cannot absolutely define a persons character or worth, the way a person represents such a story of moral behavior may not reflect directly how the person wants to be seen as such, but rather how in effect the story might serve a purpose, such as honesty, which is moral, or humor, which might be redemptive, or to imply contrast with their more mature moral perspective or character.  And there is an element of amorality as well, I think.

comments: The question of moral ambiguity was more pronounced in the third question I felt, much of the time.  Because as much as a single episode or event in a persons life cannot absolutely define a persons character or worth, the way a person represents such a story of moral behavior may not reflect directly how the person wants to be seen as such, but rather how in effect the story might serve a purpose, such as honesty, which is moral, or humor, which might be redemptive, or to imply contrast with their more mature moral perspective or character.  And there is an element of amorality as well, I think.

comments: Thank you so much for choosing me to participate in this study! I was able to grab the last spot available and I enjoyed reading all of the stories, whether they were good or bad. A lot of these stories require outside information, a better look into their lives, and are situational. A certain story in there had a situation that was tough for everyone and seemed very hard for someone so young to navigate. I hope these people are able to rest at night knowing that they did the best they could and that things will be better in the future. Please thank these people (on my behalf and because they deserve it) for sharing their stories. Good luck with the data you guys collect!

A certain story in there had a situation that was tough for everyone and seemed very hard for someone so young to navigate. I hope these people are able to rest at night knowing that they did the best they could and that things will be better in the future. Please thank these people (on my behalf and because they deserve it) for sharing their stories. Good luck with the data you guys collect!

comments: The question of moral ambiguity was more pronounced in the third question I felt, much of the time.  Because as much as a single episode or event in a persons life cannot absolutely define a persons character or worth, the way a person represents such a story of moral behavior may not reflect directly how the person wants to be seen as such, but rather how in effect the story might serve a purpose, such as honesty, which is moral, or humor, which might be redemptive, or to imply contrast with their more mature moral perspective or character.  And there is an element of amorality as well, I think.

Because as much as a single episode or event in a persons life cannot absolutely define a persons character or worth, the way a person represents such a story of moral behavior may not reflect directly how the person wants to be seen as such, but rather how in effect the story might serve a purpose, such as honesty, which is moral, or humor, which might be redemptive, or to imply contrast with their more mature moral perspective or character. comments: The question of moral ambiguity was more pronounced in the third question I felt, much of the time.  Because as much as a single episode or event in a persons life cannot absolutely define a persons character or worth, the way a person represents such a story of moral behavior may not reflect directly how the person wants to be seen as such, but rather how in effect the story might serve a purpose, such as honesty, which is moral, or humor, which might be redemptive, or to imply contrast with their more mature moral perspective or character.  And there is an element of amorality as well, I think.

comments: The question of moral ambiguity was more pronounced in the third question I felt, much of the time.  Because as much as a single episode or event in a persons life cannot absolutely define a persons character or worth, the way a person represents such a story of moral behavior may not reflect directly how the person wants to be seen as such, but rather how in effect the story might serve a purpose, such as honesty, which is moral, or humor, which might be redemptive, or to imply contrast with their more mature moral perspective or character.  And there is an element of amorality as well, I think.

comments: The question of moral ambiguity was more pronounced in the third question I felt, much of the time.  Because as much as a single episode or event in a persons life cannot absolutely define a persons character or worth, the way a person represents such a story of moral behavior may not reflect directly how the person wants to be seen as such, but rather how in effect the story might serve a purpose, such as honesty, which is moral, or humor, which might be redemptive, or to imply contrast with their more mature moral perspective or character.  And there is an element of amorality as well, I think.

title: Taking care of a patient in another country.
consent_agree: I have read the above information, have had the opportunity to have any questions about this study answered and agree to participate in this study.
comments: The question of moral ambiguity was more pronounced in the third question I felt, much of the time.  Because as much as a single episode or event in a persons life cannot absolutely define a persons character or worth, the way a person represents such a story of moral behavior may not reflect directly how the person wants to be seen as such, but rather how in effect the story might serve a purpose, such as honesty, which is moral, or humor, which might be redemptive, or to imply contrast with their more mature moral perspective or character.  And there is an element of amorality as well, I think.

comments: The question of moral ambiguity was more pronounced in the third question I felt, much of the time.  Because as much as a single episode or event in a persons life cannot absolutely define a persons character or worth, the way a person represents such a story of moral behavior may not reflect directly how the person wants to be seen as such, but rather how in effect the story might serve a purpose, such as honesty, which is moral, or humor, which might be redemptive, or to imply contrast with their more mature moral perspective or character.  And there is an element of amorality as well, I think.

comments: The question of moral ambiguity was more pronounced in the third question I felt, much of the time.  Because as much as a single episode or event in a persons life cannot absolutely define a persons character or worth, the way a person represents such a story of moral behavior may not reflect directly how the person wants to be seen as such, but rather how in effect the story might serve a purpose, such as honesty, which is moral, or humor, which might be redemptive, or to imply contrast with their more mature moral perspective or character.  And there is an element of amorality as well, I think.

comments: Thank you so much for choosing me to participate in this study! I was able to grab the last spot available and I enjoyed reading all of the stories, whether they were good or bad. I feel like I answered neutral quite a bit but I do believe a bulk of the people out of12 are not bad people (but I don't know them enough to say they are good people). A lot of these stories require outside information, a better look into their lives, and are situational. A certain story in there had a situation that was tough for everyone and seemed very hard for someone so young to navigate. I hope these people are able to rest at night knowing that they did the best they could and that things will be better in the future. Please thank these people (on my behalf and because they deserve it) for sharing their stories. Good luck with the data you guys collect!

title: Relationship crisis
consent_agree: I have read the above information, have had the opportunity to have any questions about this study answered and agree to participate in this study.
comments: The question of moral ambiguity was more pronounced in the third question I felt, much of the time.  Because as much as a single episode or event in a persons life cannot absolutely define a persons character or worth, the way a person represents such a story of moral behavior may not reflect directly how the person wants to be seen as such, but rather how in effect the story might serve a purpose, such as honesty, which is moral, or humor, which might be redemptive, or to imply contrast with their more mature moral perspective or character.  And there is an element of amorality as well, I think.

unclear: Nothing was unclear. Everything went excellent technically and comprehensively. The stories, questions, answers, and instructions were all easy to understand and navigating through the survey was simple.
comments: Thank you so much for choosing me to participate in this study! I was able to grab the last spot available and I enjoyed reading all of the stories, whether they were good or bad. I feel like I answered neutral quite a bit but I do believe a bulk of the people out of12 are not bad people (but I don't know them enough to say they are good people). A lot of these stories require outside information, a better look into their lives, and are situational. A certain story in there had a situation that was tough for everyone and seemed very hard for someone so young to navigate. I hope these people are able to rest at night knowing that they did the best they could and that things will be better in the future. Please thank these people (on my behalf and because they deserve it) for sharing their stories. Good luck with the data you guys collect!
